The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | PCB reports the bookies case to ICC
                                                   PCB reports the bookies case to ICC
                      
	 Karachi: The Pakistan Cricket Board (PCB) on Saturday admitted that it had reported to the International Cricket Council (ICC) about some Indian bookies trying to approach their players during the nations ongoing Sri Lanka tour.         
	The decision to approach the Anti-Corruption and Security Unit of the world body came after a report in a leading Urdu daily claimed earlier this week that some Indian bookmakers tried to contact the Pakistani players during the second Test in Colombo. The matter was reported by the PCB to the concerned ICC official in Sri Lanka and they took some urgent steps in this regard, a PCB statement said.         
	Onions reward         
	 Calcutta: England fast bowler Graham Onions has been rewarded with an incremental England contract, the England and Wales Cricket Board (ECB) said on Saturday. In four Tests the 26-year-old Durham quick has taken 17 wickets, including four for 58 runs on Fridays second day of the ongoing third Ashes Test against Australia here at Edgbaston.         
	He is the second player this year, Dimitri Mascarenhas of Hampshire being the other, to be added to the increment contract list. Hugh Morris, ECB managing director, said: There is no doubt that Graham thoroughly deserves his increment contract.         
	VCA elections         
	 Nagpur: Sunil Dabir has been elected president of the Vidarbha Cricket Association (VCA) here on Saturday. Shiraz Gimmi and Prakash Dixit have been elected vice-presidents. M.N. Doriarajan has been elected as the general secretary, while Rajeev Gokhale and Jaideo Kale for the posts of joint secretaries, respectively.         
	China cricket         
	 Mohali: International Cricket Council CEO Haroon Lorgat and principal advisor I.S. Bindra will be in China next week to take stock of crickets progress in the country. We are ready to help them in every possible manner, Bindra said.           STAFF REPORTER amp; AGENCIES                                                                                                                   
